<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by Arhu on 10-17-2000 09:58 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Cybu: ~[i]if I'm not mistaking I know some (text based) RPG in which backstab can only be the first attack you do.[/i]~
And that is reasonable, considering the actual meaning of [i]back[/i]stabbing. BG did this and even linked it to Hide in Shadows, which is also understandable, though it made a thief too powerful, and if not that, it at least led to save-reload-reload "gameplay". In the end, I used a thief to quickly dispatch almost anything in BG, while my fighters and mages stood around twiddling their thumbs, as Goe already described.

Sure it would be quite a story to hear about a legendary master thief (or ninja in this case) with unrivalled abilities, who could hide in shadows anytime and assassinated an entire army while no one has ever seen him, but it would be pretty boring if you could do such things, too. Someone here hinted that a thief's life is normally [i]not[/i] easy, and it's just fine that way.
Besides.. how would one backstab a knight who is clad in full plate armour? In open fights, a thief is normally lost, but his agility might prove to be useful at last. So, though the term "backstabbing" implies kind of a different meaning, a free attack is all right.

------------------
Arhu
[i]"You will always be lucky if you know how to make friends with strange cats."[/i] - Colonial American proverb</TEXTAREA>
